---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { href } from '../lib/site';
import { STATUS_META, CLAIM_STATUS_ORDER } from '../lib/claims';
---

<BaseLayout title="Note to Researchers" narrow description="How to read this site, what the status glyphs mean, and how to contribute a claim.">
  <header class="mb-8">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-2">Orientation</p>
    <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl text-[var(--color-ink)]">Note to Researchers</h1>
    <p class="ui text-[var(--color-muted)] mt-2 leading-relaxed">
      This site is built for two readers at once: a visitor who wants the phenomenon in plain language,
      and a researcher who wants a workbench of discrete, improvable claims. Here is how to read it, and
      how to add to it.
    </p>
  </header>

  <div class="prose">
    <h2>The single rule that makes this trustworthy</h2>
    <p>
      Every claim wears a status, and that status is rendered straight from the file — never upgraded to
      make the work look more finished. An <em>open</em> gap is marked as openly as a <em>derived</em>
      result. The visible humility is the point: you can trust the green marks because the grey ones are
      not hidden.
    </p>

    <h2>The status glyphs</h2>
    <ul>
      {CLAIM_STATUS_ORDER.map((s) => (
        <li>
          <span class={`glyph-${STATUS_META[s].key}`}>{STATUS_META[s].glyph}</span>
          {' '}<strong>{STATUS_META[s].label}</strong> — {STATUS_META[s].blurb}
        </li>
      ))}
      <li>
        <span class="mono text-xs border border-dashed border-[var(--color-rule-strong)] rounded px-1.5 py-0.5">Background</span>
        {' '}<strong>Reference</strong> — {STATUS_META.reference.blurb} It carries no claim glyph, by design.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      A status is promoted only when an actual argument earns it, and that argument is written into the
      claim itself. Promotion is never cosmetic.
    </p>

    <h2>Two ways through the site</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>As a reader:</strong> start with <a href={href('/guide')}>the Guide</a>, a narrative
        reading order from premise to predictions. The <a href={href('/foundation')}>Foundation</a> and
        <a href={href('/demarcation')}>Demarcation</a> sections carry the axioms and the criteria.</li>
      <li><strong>As a researcher:</strong> the <a href={href('/derivations')}>Derivations</a> workbench
        lists every result as a self-contained target; the <a href={href('/derivation-chain')}>derivation
        chain</a> shows how they hang together; the <a href={href('/open-gaps')}>open gaps</a> page is the
        honest to-do list.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to contribute a claim</h2>
    <p>
      Claims live as Markdown files under <span class="mono">content/</span> — the single source of truth.
      The site is a pure renderer: add a file with honest frontmatter and the index, the chain, the open-gaps
      page, and the dependency relationships all update on the next build. Nothing else to wire up.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Create <span class="mono">content/&lt;layer&gt;/your-claim.md</span> with the frontmatter
        fields <span class="mono">title, slug, layer, status, summary, depends_on, order, updated</span>
        (the schema is enforced at build).</li>
      <li>Set <span class="mono">depends_on</span> to the slugs it rests on — that draws the chain and the
        “rests on / supports” footers automatically.</li>
      <li>Record the reasoning in <span class="mono">transcripts/</span> and link it with a
        <span class="mono">provenance:</span> path; it surfaces on the claim's page.</li>
      <li>Mark the status honestly. If it's a target rather than a result, that's what
        <span class="mono">status: open</span> or <span class="mono">provisional</span> is for.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>The full loop, including how to run the site locally, is in <span class="mono">WORKFLOW.md</span> at the repo root.</p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
